NASHVILLE Tenn.  The Tennessee Department of Mental Health and Substance Abuse Services TDMHSAS is receiving more than 53 million in additional funding from the federal government to address post-COVID mental health and substance use needs.
The supplemental block grant funding will add more than 27 million to mental health services and nearly 26 million to substance use services over the next four years. The funding is part of a 3 billion allocation included in the American Rescue Plan signed into law in March.
The new funding comes on top of significant supplemental funding from the federal government and new investment of state dollars. TDMHSAS has received an additional 55 million in COVID relief funding from the federal government since the start of the pandemic and Governor Bill Lee and the Tennessee General Assembly increased the departments budget for next fiscal year by more than 44.1 million.
The most recent rounds of federal funding supplement the states existing Mental Health Block Grant and Substance Abuse Block Grants. New dollars will expand the availability of evidence-based treatment services strengthen the statewide network of crisis services support the continued and expanded use of telehealth services respond to the unique needs of children and more. TDMHSAS and federal partners are both allowing room for mental health and substance use treatment agencies across the state to design programs that meet their communities unique needs.
With the outpouring of support for mental health and substance use needs in our state we have a priceless opportunity to bring about significant change and make a difference for Tennesseans who are struggling. The mental health and substance use impacts brought on by the stresses of the pandemic are with us and these generous investments at both the state and federal levels are going to make sure we and our community behavioral health providers can continue to rise to meet the need said TDMHSAS Commissioner Marie Williams LCSW. We are tremendously grateful to our amazing network of providers across the state who answer the call and respond with compassionate care to help people find new lives in recovery.
During the pandemic the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention surveyed people in Tennessee and across the nation on feelings of anxiety and depression. Tennesseans self-reported symptoms of anxiety and depression at rates of more than 40 which is more than double the normal prevalence of any mental illness in a given year.
Tennessee also saw a tragic spike in drug overdoses in the first few months of the pandemic. Thanks to the work of the Regional Overdose Prevention Specialists and other harm reduction groups the rate of drug overdose returned to normal levels but still too many Tennesseans are dying from a preventable cause.
To learn more about services available for Tennesseans who have no insurance or no way to pay visit our website TN.govbehavioral-health
A sedative drug used for animals is now showing up on the streets of Nashville causing public health concerns.
The mitigations of Xylazine is starting to show up as the cause of death in autopsies as well as in drug busts Metro Police's top drug officer says. The drug is meant to be used as a sedative for animals such as cattle and not approved for human consumption.
The issue with this new drug is you can't override the affects of it with Narcan like you can with other drugs. Xylazine can reportedly leave open sores and even cause the removal of limbs if it doesn't take you life first.
One Metro Council member said he saw the effects of this drug first hand when he visited a homeless camp in his district.
I've recently had a homeless camp closed in my district says Metro Councilmember Jordan Huffman. And I have seen what Xylazine does to the human body first hand. Going in these camps and seeing the decay and the loss of limbs is extremely traumatic. Not only just or those who see it but my goodness the people that have to deal with it.
Metro Police Sergeant Mike Hotz says about 80 of the fentanyl tested in their crime lab tested positive for Xylazine. He notes the amounts the lab saw were traced meaning Xylazine is present in the drug supply but not necessarily in quantities large enough to have the narcotic effect to get a person high.
Unfortunately in my personal and professional opinion the Xylazine is here on scene in Nashville's drug supply and that poses significant public health and public safety issues to our citizens says Sergeant Hotz. And it creates not only a problem for treatment of substance use disorder but it also creates other public health problems with the open wounds.
Sergeant Hotz says Metro Police believes Xylazine is coming in from the Southern border from places like Mexico and Central America. It is being sold along with fentanyl as well as mixed in with drugs such as meth.
Xylazine has been on the State of Tennessee's radar since 2022 according to Metro Police. Now it is being seen in areas across Nashville.
Doctors at Vanderbilt Medical University Center have been made aware of this new public health issue. They appreciate Metro Police informing them of the problem so medical professionals can start collecting data on how best to treat the significant wounds.
