The list of priorities for lawmakers as they convened in Nashville last week for the start of the legislative session was lengthy.
Of those one of the topics likely to get the most attention this session is how lawmakers address the states growing opioid crisis.
According to state Department of Mental Health and Substance Abuse Service estimates 284412 Tennessee adults used heroin andor opioid pain relievers non-medically in 2016. Another 33325 Tennesseans ages 12-17 did the same.
Rep. Eddie Smith R-Knoxville has made it his goal this session to pass legislation geared toward helping the latter population by implementing recovery high schools schools that serve teens struggling with using drugs and alcohol across the state.
This is affecting everybody it doesnt matter your socioeconomic class Smith said about the crisis. Its affecting everybody across the board. This year we saw the son of the Nashville mayor pass away because of this. It doesnt matter if youre rich poor black or white everybody is affected by this. This is an issue.
Overall at least 1631 Tennesseans died from drug overdoses in 2016 up 12 percent from the 2015 but experts think the reported number is low due to inconsistencies in how counties investigate and report deaths.
How the schools would work
The high schools would be set up as non-residential treatment facilities that combine counseling and drug treatment with a high school curriculum. The high schools would serve as an option for parents wanting their child to get help and give juvenile court judges another tool in their tool belt.
Students would be dropped off and picked up like a normal school but the days may be a little longer than a normal school.
Hellen Ross McNabb regional vice president Mona Blanton-Kitts said the organization and Knox County Schools spent a good portion of 2017 before Smiths proposed legislation researching recovery high schools with the thought of possibly starting one in Knox County.
It allows the child to receive both a quality education and good treatment without having to sacrifice one or the other 
Credits would be transferable and diplomas would be from the school they were originally set to graduate from Smith said.
We dont want the stigma of a recovery high school to follow them into their career path in the future he said.
Recovery high schools can be effective
Andy Finch is an assistant professor of counseling and researcher at Vanderbilt University. Finch served as the former school director at Community High School a recovery school in Nashville that closed in 2008 and is considered a national expert on recovery high schools.
He said he is impressed and excited that state lawmakers are beginning to study the schools.
I would say with some confidence that the program is likely to work for a family in many different ways  my feeling is the peer support that is present in a recovery high school is the most important factor. We cant say that imperially but its something that the recovery high schools provide that really no other setting is going to provide he said.
In a 2017 published study Finch found recovery high school students were twice as likely to report complete abstinence from alcohol marijuana and other drugs 59 percent to 30 percent at their six month follow-up than students who did not attend a recovery high school.
Likewise in preliminary analysis for a not yet published study Finch said high school graduation rates for recovery high school students is at least 20 points higher than those who do not attend a recovery high school for at least 30 days.
Blanton-Kitts was thrilled that the state was beginning to look at recovery high schools because they work she said.
What we know is long-term treatment is much better than short-term treatment and treatment in the community and environment especially in a school-based setting is much better than taking a child out of the environment if possible.
What works best is them not going back to the same environment where the same triggers are she continued. If there is a recovery high school to go to it would extend their sober living and would continue their treatment they have been in.
Finch said there are around 40 recovery high schools across the country and only one in Tennessee Ridgecrest Academy in Nashville.
Ridgecrest had two students with the USA TODAY NETWORK-Tennessee wrote about it in the fall of 2016 and Finch said he didnt think the school had any students currently. Administrators at Ridgecrest could not be reached for comment.
The reason Community High School failed and Ridgecrest has struggled is due to the cost to families Finch said. Any cost to families is a barrier he said. Ridgecrests tuition was 25000 in 2016 and Community High Schools was around 12000 when it closed.
A lot of families have already spent money on treatment for kids  theyve already spent thousands on treatment and counseling services and medication Finch said.
Smith's proposal is for public recovery schools not private.
Making a dent
Under Smiths proposed legislation the state would set up three recovery high schools one in each grand division and would pull county state federal and grant funding to open the schools.
He expects the plan to cost about 100000 a year per school a figure that could rise but he points to Department of Mental Health figures that show the state spent 50.9 million in state and federal funds in fiscal year 2018 on adult substance abuse treatment but just 3.2 million on adolescent treatment plus another 170000 for Juvenile Recovery Court.
The proposed legislation does not stipulate how many employees would be needed but Smith said he imagines current school system employees would make the move to the school. The proposed legislation assumes existing facilities would be used.
Weve got to do more to reach our kids Smith said. Were throwing money at the back end of the problem. We need to be throwing it at the front end.
Of all the things we could fund with knowing we have a surplus going into the next year and going into the future this is one area where putting money is well worth the investment for what it will do Smith continued.
Knoxvilles Metropolitan Drug Commission Executive Director Karen Pershing agreed.
Either we intercept the problem in the early years when the behaviors start or were going to pay a whole lot more when theyre adults and the consequences will be a whole lot greater for all of us she said.
