TobyMac's son is one of hundreds of people to die in 2019 across greater Nashville as a result of an overdose involving fentanyl  an epidemic health experts on Wednesday said they expect to worsen this year.
Truett Foster McKeehan the Christian rap artist's 21-year-old son is one of 424 people who died of drug overdoses in Davidson County with 64 of those deaths involving fentanyl Metro Public Health Department records show.
Provisional data for 2019 shows a 28 increase from 2018 said Trevor Henderson Nashvilles opioid response coordinator. Last year's numbers are provisional he noted and may increase as cases are closed.
Moreover projections for fatal drug overdoses for 2020 show the trend will likely continue to worsen with fentanyl remaining the primary contributor health officials said.
McKeehan was found unresponsive at a home in the city's Radnor neighborhood on Oct. 23. Autopsy and toxicology results show he died with a cocktail of drugs in his system.
Davidson County Medical Examiner Feng Li ruled McKeehan's cause of death to be acute combined drug intoxication stemming from an accidental overdose of fentanyl and amphetamines.
Fentanyl is a synthetic opioid that can be fatal in doses no larger than a few grains of sand said Dr. David Edwards chief of the division of pain medicine at Vanderbilt University Medical Center.
In powder form Edwards said. It's just a little bit of dust in a small vial but enough micrograms can kill you.
Its cheaper to produce than heroin but approximately 50 times stronger so some drug traffickers mix fentanyl into their drug supply to inflate profits. Fentanyl is also increasingly found combined with cocaine and methamphetamine both of which have caused more deaths in recent years.
McKeehan's toxicology findings show he had 8.7 nanograms per milliliter of blood of fentanyl in his system and 7.9 nanograms per milliliter of blood of metabolized fentanyl in his system.
In deaths related to fentanyl Edwards said blood concentrations can vary widely but in a New York state review of autopsies representing people who died with multiple drugs in their system an average of 8.2 nanograms per milliliters of blood with a range of 1.1 up to 38 led to their deaths.
Drug use in Middle TennesseeA spike in overdose deaths in Nashville may be tied to fentanyl health officials warn
In Li's summary report he wrote McKeehan had a history of drug and alcohol abuse as well as possible nitrous oxide use. Nitrous oxide is commonly known as laughing gas. He was discovered unresponsive in bed by a friend conducting a welfare check on Oct. 23.
A toxicology report also found McKeehan had adderall and marijuana among other drugs in his system at the time of death.
It was not immediately known where McKeehan got the drugs.
Metro police spokeswoman Kris Mumford said the case remained open on Wednesday.
Other Middle TN cases
More than 9100 people died of drug overdoses in Tennessee between 2013 and 2018 according to state death data. More than 70 of those deaths were at least partially caused by opioids including fentanyl.
A 26-year-old Bonnaroo Music and Arts Festival attendee died in 2019 after he overdosed on drugs including fentanyl.
Ryan Dunleavy of Brentwood was found the morning of June 15 in the venue's Manchester's campgrounds his autopsy results show. He was transported to Unity Medical Center in Manchester where he was pronounced dead.
According to a toxicology report Dunleavy had drugs including fentanyl MDMA ecstasy and clozapine in his system when he died. Autopsy results show Dunleavy's manner of death was accidental.
In some of the overdose cases across Tennessee authorities have arrested the decedent's dealer. It's part of a strategy to fight the opioid epidemic.
One month before Dunleavy overdosed  after nearly a year and a half of extensive investigative work  Metro Nashville police charged 32-year-old Christopher James Floyd with murder in connection to a woman's 2017 death.
Authorities said Roberts provided the mix of heroin and fentanyl that killed Sara Roberts who fatally overdosed at the East Thompson Lane home where she lived with her mother.
An autopsy found the 33-year-old Nashville woman died of acute drug toxicity from a combination of alcohol and heroin laced with fentanyl.
Floyd remained jailed in Davidson County Wednesday awaiting trial on more than 100000 bond.
