About 75 percent of participants in Norman's court have used opioids or heroin which provides a similar high to pills but is cheaper though it may not be the person's primary addiction leaders say. Abbott said in 2016 208 recovery court participants were primarily addicted to heroin. Two years earlier it was only 94 people.
Norman and Crosson say there is need to expand the programs into rural areas which can have fewer community-based resources such as inpatient treatment providers. Norman's court in Nashville is the only one in the state that provides its own housing. Others turn to community resources. There also is a need to reach more women I really do have people calling me every day begging for beds Norman said.
Statewide recovery court participants spend 12 to 24 months in a program. Norman says that's often years shorter than a prison term and it's cheaper than incarceration when considering daily housing costs. The judge estimates 33000 savings by sending a person through his program.
There are no fences with barbed wire or cells at Davidson County Drug Court. Just long-term treatment that despite a laundry list of strict rules participants believe is helping them beat addiction.
Or as 23-year-old David Faust says helping him learn to feel emotion without turning to substances. He and others in the program want the public to know that this is not a life they chose nor could stop.
When people are kids they don't just grow up and say 'I want to grow up and be a heroin addict'  Faust said.
His addiction started in high school. I ended up smoking a bunch of pot taking pills he said. I started taking stronger pain pills it's like a progression you know. Eventually I started shooting up pills. It was getting pretty expensive and heroin's pretty cheap so it just makes sense to go to heroin.
He worked and lived in Nashville.
It wasn't ever enough money to support my habits. I had to do extra stuff he says. Extra stuff like breaking into houses and cars according to public records.
I've been to a bunch of rehabs before this one he says. But they were like 28-day rehabs. That's no real clean time or anything. So I'd just get out and keep doing the same thing.
He started in drug court in September 2015 when his lawyers presented an ultimatum drug court or prison.
Jail's a lot easier he says. The residential program is strict Men and women do not interact. They work in the kitchen and garden. If someone doesn't do chores their dorm mates can be punished. Often that's a sentence to wear an old-fashioned black-and-white-striped jail jumpsuit.
But it works.
It's probably the worst best thing that's happened to me Faust says.
Around here you really find out what pisses you off. You learn to deal with that in the form of not getting messed up. You also learn what makes you happy.
