That effort can run into hurdles erected by silence by others with drug addictions who fear speaking out and getting into trouble he said.
They need to know if you sell something and somebody dies you can be held accountable he said. And you can be held accountable for their death ... Were hoping itll make them think twice about dealing these drugs.
He sees the murder charge as opposed to a drug distribution charge as another way to combat the opioid crisis.
Were trying to get rid of the drugs no matter what. This is another tool we have to fight this epidemic.
Officials reported at least 1451 people died from drug overdoses in Tennessee in 2015 but the true number is unknown and likely higher by the hundreds according to a USA TODAY NETWORK-Tennessee investigation.
National statistics from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention show more than 33000 people died in 2015 from opioids.
