Healthy Tennessee will hold a summit entitled Working Together to Solve the Opioid Crisis.
This summit is the first of its kind and will be focused on solutions collaboration and action.
Manny Sethi M.D. is president of Healthy Tennessee and is an orthopaedic trauma surgeon.
Tennessee has become a hot bed destination for tourism in recent years but unfortunately we have also become a haven for opioid abuse leading to a record number of deaths in the Volunteer State.
The numbers attributed to the opioid crisis are staggering. Just this week the Tennessee Department of Health reported that drug overdose deaths killed more Tennesseans than ever before a trend that has been repeated for six years in a row.
Tennessee has one of the highest opioid overdose death rates in the country. Three people die every day in Tennessee due to opioids  more than traffic-related fatalities.
The opioid crisis is not just a rural problem as 1-in-5 opioid overdose deaths in 2016 were right here in Davidson County. In fact deaths involving fentanyl an incredibly potent synthetic opioid are up 70 percent since last year. Fentanyl is sometimes found in counterfeits illegally smuggled in to our country and has now surpassed heroin now as the deadliest drug in Nashville.
The opioid crisis also has had an economic impact on our state as the University of Tennessee found that there is a direct correlation between opioid use unemployment and a decline in labor force participation.
Building a healthy Tennessee and fighting this opioid epidemic we face are directly linked. Almost a decade ago my wife Maya and I started Healthy Tennessee with the goal of improving health across Tennessee.
Harnessing the power of local communities and hundreds of volunteers we conducted health fairs in small towns and large cities across our great state. But one thing we quickly realized is that all too often organizations like Healthy Tennessee and others operate in silos where one hand does not know what the other is doing.
In other words our state has many important and effective community health organizations but we often tend to duplicate efforts as we dont collaborate or communicate.
Collaboration is key to breaking the silo
To try and break down these silos over the past two years we have partnered with the Blue Cross Blue Shield of Tennessee Health Foundation to bring over 150 organizations together in summits across Tennessee.
Through these efforts we developed a better sense of community and developed shared goals forging the path toward a powerful network of community health organizations across our state.
For example from these meetings came the concept of creating the first of its kind statewide list-serve to connect stakeholders from Memphis to Mountain City breaking down silos with one click.
Through our health fairs and summits across Tennessee we have seen firsthand the impact opioid addiction has had in every corner of our state. We have met with incredible organizations and individuals who are committed to solve the opioid crisis but face the same challenges I mention above  working in silos .
Across Tennessee when it comes to prevention treatment and rehabilitation of opioid addiction we are often at the cutting edge. But to ultimately end the opioid crisis it will take more than any single action and will require a collaborative effort from all stakeholders involved there is no magic bullet.
As we have done previously for community health organizations I felt Healthy Tennessee needed to take the next step to collaborate on a more granular level and have these committed individuals and organizations from across the state together under one roof to develop strategies and action plans to solve the opioid crisis in Tennessee once and for all.
First of its kind summit will address and create solutions
This week Healthy Tennessee will hold a summit entitled Working Together to Solve the Opioid Crisis. This summit is the first of its kind in our state and will be focused on solutions collaboration and action.
The summit will include faith leaders law enforcement elected officials the private sector and non-profit organizations who are working on the front lines to solve the opioid crisis.
We are bringing together these individuals and groups to collaborate and understand how they can work together to ultimately solve the opioid crisis in Tennessee and beyond.
The summit will also hear from candidates for statewide office  Congressman Marsha Blackburn former Governor Phil Bredesen former Nashville Mayor Karl Dean and businessman Bill Lee  to hear how they will collaborate with these individuals and organizations to solve this crisis if elected in November.
My hope is that this summit will be an important next step to break down silos open lines of communications across the state and renew a sense of collaboration to ensure that Tennessee becomes a leader in solving the opioid crisis.
Manny Sethi M.D. is president of Healthy Tennessee and is an orthopaedic trauma surgeon in Nashville.
