In mid-October a 29-year-old man was overdosing. His friends rushed him to an Ashland City emergency room.
He survived and he was released that night after receiving treatment.
Cheatham County Sheriffs Lt. Shannon Heflin said the man and two other people had purchased drugs from Haley Smith 26 of Ashland City and the victim thought he was snorting cocaine which ended up being a combination of heroin and fentanyl.
In a new twist for criminal justice in Tennessee Smith now faces charges of attempted second-degree murder possessing schedule I drugs and possession of drug paraphernalia in connection to the near-fatal overdose.
Just over a month later the Cheatham County Sheriffs Office reported four overdoses in one weekend one of which was fatal.
Evidence related to that overdose the death of a 30-year-old Chapmansboro man led the Cheatham County Sheriffs Office to Christopher Stefko 39 on Nov. 25.
Investigators believe Stefko traveled from Nashville to Cheatham County to sell drugs to the victim. Undercover investigators arranged another heroin deal then arrested Stefko and took him to the Cheatham County Jail.
In addition to drug charges Stefko has been charged with second-degree murder.
Holding dealers accountable
Murder charges against alleged drug dealers in fatal or near-fatal drug overdoses has become increasingly common in recent years in Tennessee where opioid deaths increased 12 percent in 2016.
The Drug Policy Alliance points out that other states including Delaware Kansas and Wyoming among others also have drug-induced homicide laws.
They need to know if you sell something and somebody dies you can be held accountable Metro Nashville Police Lt. Carlos Lara said previously. And you can be held accountable for their death. ... Were hoping itll make them think twice about dealing these drugs.
Prosecuting such cases is a tool that can deter people from dispensing and using opioids said Sumner County District Attorney Ray Whitley.
Cheatham County District Attorney Ray Crouch said he knew of several cases like these prosecuted in his district in recent years and the number will continue to rise.
The 2010 Tennessee Code specifies that second-degree murder could be defined in part as the killing of another that results from the unlawful distribution of any Schedule I or Schedule II drug when the drug is the proximate cause of the death of the user.
Crouch said since the statute was amended there's been a huge uptick in drug-related homicide charges particularly since opioid deaths have increased on a national scale.
State officials reported at least 1451 drug overdose deaths in Tennessee in 2015 though the actual number is likely higher by the hundreds a previous USA TODAY NETWORK  Tennessee report found.
The following year the estimate jumped to at least 1631 drug overdose deaths statewide according to the Tennessee Department of Health.
In Cheatham County more than 90 heroin overdoses  including more than five deaths  have been reported from January through September.
State data show deaths from fentanyl a synthetic opioid upped from 169 in 2015 to 294 in 2016 a previous report states.
Crouch said he believes prosecuting dealers selling fentanyl  That's what's killing everybody  with murder charges will have a deterring effect.
Lesser charges such as sale of a controlled substance could land the offender anything from a misdemeanor to a low-level felony he said whereas the minimum time serving a second-degree murder sentence is 15 years.
Crouch said the biggest challenge to prosecuting drug-induced homicide cases is whether there was a proper death scene investigation.
If law enforcement officials initially responding to the scene don't recognize drug overdose symptoms he said then the body might not be properly examined and there might not even be an autopsy performed.
I do think several overdose deaths have gone by in Tennessee where someone could have been charged Crouch said though he credited law enforcement officials for becoming more aware of the problem noting that he's seeing improvement in investigations.
