In recent years Tennessee policymakers have enacted a series of measures to combat the state's growing opioid problem
2015 Lawmakers enact legislation tightening the requirements for medical directors and owners of pain management clinics. The new law requires medical directors or owners of pain clinics to be licensed physicians who hold required continuing medical education and sub-specialty certifications in pain medicine.
2015 The Intractable Pain Treatment Act is repealed with the support of the states district attorneys and the Tennessee Bureau of Investigation. The 2001 measure included a Pain Patients Bill of Rights which gave patients a great amount of responsibility to choose opiate medications as a first line of treatment and physicians were required either to provide requested opiate medication or refer patients to physicians who would.
2014 Tennessee Gov. Bill Haslam announces a seven-point plan to address the state's opioid abuse problem that includes public education law enforcement and regulatory oversight of the medical community.
2014 New guidelines issued by the Tennessee Department of Health set limits on the daily doses of opioids doctors may prescribe and spell out protocols for giving the drugs to women of child-bearing age and establish new certification requirements for pain medication specialists.
2013 Dispensing of controlled substances by pain management clinics is prohibited.
2013 Tennessee begins to require health care professionals to check the Controlled Substance Monitoring Database before prescribing a controlled substance.
2013 Legislation limits to 30 days prescriptions for drugs categorized as Schedule II and Schedule III which include a range of opioid medications. The law also requires physicians to perform urine drug tests if they prescribe these medications beyond 30 days.
2013 A new law to combat prescription fraud requires medical professionals to use tamper-resistant paper for all written prescriptions.
2012 The Prescription Safety Act sponsored by Sen. Ken Yager R-Harriman is the first sweeping legislation to address opioid abuse. It expanded the required use of the state's prescription drug database originally created as a research tool requiring pharmacists to check the database before filling prescriptions update the database once a week instead of once per month and making the database available to law enforcement. The law also allowed pharmacists and the Department of Health to share prescription information across state lines and elevated some types of doctor-shopping to a felony.
