The opioid crisis has been devastating to Tennessee. And it's getting worse.
More than 9100 people have died of drug overdoses in Tennessee between 2013 and 2018 according to state death data. More than 70 of those deaths were at least partially caused by opioids including prescription painkillers heroin or fentanyl.
The ongoing opioid crisis  the deadliest drug epidemic in American history  was largely sparked by the overprescription and abuse of prescription medications. Painkillers like OxyContin were prescribed frequently and in large dosages leading many patients to become dependent or addicted to these drugs.
PAINKILLERSThis pain clinic nurse gave a patient 51 pills a day. And she kept her license.
Tennessee later adopted laws and regulations to cut back these prescriptions but the damage was already done. People who had become addicted to prescription painkillers could still feed their addiction with heroin or black market pills.
Opioid prescriptions have now become weaker and less common in Tennessee but deaths have only grown.
As more people have flocked to the black market the drugs they use have become deadlier.
Heroin is chemically similar to prescription painkillers but far stronger and more dangerous. And heroin is often laced with fentanyl an exceptionally powerful synthetic opioid that is about 100 times more potent than morphine. A lethal dose is no larger than a few grains of sand.
Fentanyl was once virtually unknown outside of hospitals but has now grown to become one of the deadliest substances in America.
Why is our opioid crisis getting worse
You can pretty much explain it with a one-word answer fentanyl said Trevor Henderson Nashvilles opioid response coordinator.
HOW TO HELPNarcan a life-saving anti-overdose drug is now sold online in Tennessee
Many states have begun to turn a corner on the opioid crisis but Tennessee has not.
Nationwide overdose deaths dropped 2.2 between March 2018 and March 2019 according to the U.S. Census Bureau which tallies and estimates drug fatalities.
Deaths have also dropped dramatically in many of the states that have been hit hardest by the opioid crisis Ohio -12.4 Pennsylvania -11.5 Michigan -10.3 Florida -6.6 and Kentucky -8.2.
In Tennessee deaths rose 7.3 over the same period.
Those deaths are not entirely caused by opioids however.
This census data includes all drug deaths and Tennessee has also recorded a rise in deaths linked to methamphetamine and cocaine. Cocaine deaths dropped in 2018 but have risen overall since the opioid crisis began.
Many of these deaths are the result of intermingled drugs combining stimulants and opioids in a way that magnifies the danger of both according to law enforcement.
And fentanyl is increasingly found laced into not only heroin but also meth and cocaine.
We have been sounding the alarm and beating the drum so much trying to warn people that what they are buying may not be what it appears said T.J. Jordan assistant director of the Tennessee Bureau of Investigations drug division. What you take today may simply kill you tomorrow. And no one is heeding that warning.
