The Metro Public Health Department in Nashville announced its participation in a new text notification program to alert the public of spikes in overdose activity. MPHD will be the only jurisdiction in Tennessee participating in this new project with Partnership to End Addiction. Public health officials hope to reach those who are at risk of suffering an overdose and their families quickly by text notifications.
Alarming levels of drug overdoses are being reported in Nashville and Middle Tennessee. More people have died in the first four months of 2021 due to drug overdose than in the first four months of 2020 and drug overdoses have steadily risen over the past five years according to MPHD.
Those interested in receiving text updates should text SPIKE to 1-855-963-5669. If you are interested in receiving more information you can send an email to Opioid.ResponseNashville.gov
MPHD continuously monitors data about drug use and outcomes across different communities in Middle Tennessee and uses several data sources to detect increases in overdoses occurring in the community.
Josh Love an epidemiologist for MPHD said the department studies changes in the number of fatal and nonfatal overdoses ages and locations and the types of drugs used. Spikes are classified as a number higher than the daily average. The summer is a peak season for overdose spiking but prediction is hard which is why the text program will help get information to the public as it becomes available.
MPHD also recommends family and friends of those at risk of a drug overdose recognize common signs such as unresponsiveness light blue or grey coloring on lips and fingertips shallow breaths and gurgling or snoring sounds.
When encountering a person who may have overdosed call 911 and stay with the person until help arrives.
The MPHD website has information about proper drug disposal drug lock boxes a syringe services program and more.
If you or someone you know is struggling with addiction call or text the Tennessee REDLINE at 1-800-889-9789 for substance abuse treatment referrals.
