Tennessees outgoing chief addiction expert said the only way to make a real dent in overdose deaths is the controversial practice of using opioids to reduce cravings.
If you truly want to make an impact you have to embrace that practice said Dr. Stephen Loyd who resigned effective Monday from his job as medical director for the states substance abuse services division.
Loyd 50 left his job to accept the role of co-medical director at a private drug rehab center JourneyPure at the River in Murfreesboro.
Loyd did so after working for the state for two years making hundreds of presentations across Tennessee on drug addiction and serving as an advisor on Gov. Bill Haslams new 30 million plan to battle the opioid epidemic. Most of the money would be used for addiction treatment with some going toward more law enforcement and prevention efforts.
At least 1631 Tennesseans died from drug overdoses  most of those from pain pills called opioids  in 2016 a 12 percent jump from 2015 according to the Tennessee Department of Health.
Loyd said Haslams plan to battle the opioid epidemic is a very good start.
Is it enough he added. No.
Loyd  himself a recovering addict  said medical professionals need to embrace the practice of using opioids like Buprenorphine Sub Oxone and methadone to get addicts off drugs like heroin and Oxycodone.
Any opioid however has a significant chance for abuse making their use controversial in the recovery community.
 More Loyd former pill abuser now battles drug epidemic in Tennessee
 More Governor unveils 30 million plan to battle TN opioid crisis
Loyd and several other Tennessee addiction specialists agree the best approach to recovery is inpatient rehab treatment followed by outpatient monitoring and support groups.
But Loyd and two other experts  Vanderbilt medical school Professor Dan Lonergan and Cumberland Heights chief medical officer Chapman Sledge  also agree residential treatment is too expensive for or otherwise not accessible to most addicts who need it.
So Lonergan said he agrees 100 percent with Loyd that doctors and public health officials should embrace using Buprenorphine and other drugs to wean addicts off their drugs of choice.
Lonergan also said studies have shown medication-assisted treatment is more effective than abstinence-based programs.
In a statement issued Wednesday Feb. 7 the state Department of Mental Health and Substance Abuse Services indicated Tennessee would be open to the use of Sub Oxone and methadone.
We know that no single method of treatment works for all patients with substance use disorder Commissioner Marie Williams said in the statement but we believe that if properly prescribed administered and monitored harm reduction drugs can be effective in helping some patients overcome their addiction issues.
Sledge from Cumberland Heights isnt as quick to embrace using opioids for recovery. He said he has been having good results with an opioid-blocking drug called naltrexone found in the Vivitrol injections some recovering addicts get to keep them from using.
Loyd said the main reason he switched jobs was to get back to directly treating patients.
His new boss said JourneyPure is open to all approaches and to matching patients with best treatment for their individual needs. Right now JourneyPure offers abstinence-based treatment at four residential facilities across the state.
JourneyPure is based on innovation and research said Sam MacMaster co-founder and chief clinical officer for the Nashville-based company. We are open to matching individuals with the best possible service to help end this epidemic and overdose deaths.
The company now uses Vivitrol for some residential patients. JourneyPure provides medication-assisted recovery including using Sub Oxone in some outpatient clinics.
