NASHVILLE Tenn.--The Tennessee Board of Judicial Conduct is calling on the State Legislature to remove a local judge from her post due to alleged substance abuse issues and a failure to comply with terms of her previous suspensions.
In a  the recommendation by the board centers around Judge A. Melissa Boyd who serves as a Criminal Court Judge in the 30th Judicial District in Shelby County.
According to the recommendation Judge Boyd has received two public reprimands since taking the role in September 2022. One reprimand cited from May 8 2023 states within weeks of Judge Boyd assuming office she solicited resources and cash donations on social media for the benefit of a third party. Judge Boyd is said to have ignored the Board's inquiry into the matter but agreed to accept the reprimand.
On May 22 2023 Judge Boyd was suspended following allegations from a campaign manager who also had personal relations with the judge. According to affidavits filed by the former campaign manager the woman claims she discovered a plate with a spoon and what is believed to have been cocaine in the Judge's home closet. The affidavit states Judge Boyd admitted it was cocaine to the campaign manager and also admitted to smoking marijuana multiple times since being elected.
The affidavits go on to allege Judge Boyd was also seen outside the campaign manager's property in January 2023 taking pictures of the woman's car and property which she then texted to the woman. The affidavit stated Judge Boyd allegedly sent more texts asking who is the whore seriously Judge Body also allegedly sent the woman pictures of her prior marriage license and information about her divorce which made the woman feel disturbed.
The Board memo adds following the suspensions the Board gave Judge Boyd an opportunity to resign in November of last year but did not respond nor had she addressed substance abuse issues. In December of last year Judge Boyd was indicted on charges of coercion of a witness and harassment. Judge Boyd responded she had ultimately entered a rehab facility after the specified required dates and accused the Board of piling on her by keeping her off the bench.
