At least six more of his patients had nonfatal overdoses between 2014 and 2016 and one of those patients overdosed three times state health records showed.
He admitted distributing opioids to four different patients without legitimate medical needs on 18 different occasions between December 2014 and December 2015 the news release indicated.
He also admitted prescribing hydrocodone to a patient without underlying issues in January 2016.
The indictment indicated he routinely prescribed opioids and other drugs without legitimate medical purpose.
A joint investigation by The Tennessean and The Indianapolis Star in 2019 brought the case to the attention of the U.S. Attorney's Office which stepped in to investigate over local prosecutors. Local investigators had used an undercover informant to gain video footage inside Rinehart's clinic.
Before the doctor moved to Indiana the Tennessee Board of Medical Examiners agreed to suspend Rineharts medical license if he agreed not to attempt to practice medicine in Tennessee.
The news release from the U.S. Attorney's Office refers to Rinehart as a former doctor.
Department of Justice units including the Medicare Fraud Strike Force and the Appalachian Regional Prescription Opioid Strike Force were involved in the investigation as was the federal Department of Health and Human Services the Tennessee Bureau of Investigation and the local district attorney's office.
