A former Columbia doctor pleaded guilty to one count of unlawful distribution of controlled substances in Federal Court on Monday in a victory for the nation's ongoing battle against the misuse of opioids.
Dr. Darrel Rinehart who was previously affiliated with Maury Regional Medical Group until 2016 and later moved to Indiana where he continued to practice admitted Monday that in January 2016 he knowingly distributed hydrocodone a Schedule II controlled substance to a patient who did not have any significant underlying health issues justifying such a prescription.
A statement from the Department of Justice and United States Attorney Donald Q. Cochran of the Middle District of Tennessee also indicated Rinehart further admitted to distributing Schedule II controlled substances primarily opioids to four different patients without a legitimate medical purpose and outside the course of professional practice on 18 other occasions between December 2014 and December 2015.
The former local doctor is planned to be sentenced on July 30 2020 by Chief U.S. District Judge Waverly D. Crenshaw Jr. He faces up to 20 years in prison and up to a 1 million fine according to the federal department.
The Office of Inspector General U.S. Department of Health and Human Services The Tennessee Bueaur of Investigation and the District Attorney General for the Tennessee's 22nd Judicial District investigated the case.
Assistant Chief Kilby Macfadden and Trial Attorney William M. Grady of the Criminal Division's Fraud Section are prosecuting the case.
In March Rinehart 64 was indicted on 19 counts of prescribing controlled substances without a legitimate medical purpose after at least four of his patients died from drug overdoses according to a news release from the Department of Justice.
He was one of 32 Tennessee doctors and
medical professionals charged with crimes related to over-prescribing opioids in the national crackdown on individuals who prescribed addictive medications without justification.
After Rinehart was caught on undercover video increasing a patient's opioid prescription without any examination by a member by the Maury County Sheriff's Department the Columbia doctor's medical license was suspended by the Tennessee Board of Medical Examiners.
Maury Regional Medical Group previously said it employed Dr. Rinehart as well as other physicians of CORE Physicians an independent Columbia medical practice starting September 1 2015. Rinehart's employment was terminated approximately 15 months later on Nov. 22 2016 a spokesperson from the medical center said.
A local drug task force sent in an informant and acquired various painkillers from Rinehart who did not conduct any sort of examination of the undercover agent District Attorney Brent Cooper previously told The Daily Herald.
Because federal charges carry more time Cooper and his office chose to not prosecute Rinehart including a reckless homicide change the district attorney's office was investigating.
I am glad to see that he is being held accountable for his habits of over prescribing these dangerous drugs Cooper said Monday. He will never be able to dispense drugs again and cause harm to others.
Cooper said he would have preferred to see the federal charge include homicide.
I hope that this will give the families of these victims some peace and satisfaction as the death of their loved ones allowed us to collect the evidence that likely led to his prosecution Cooper said. Opioids are still a huge problem and causing death on a daily basis.
Although charges connected the former Columbia doctor to four fatal overdoses an investigation carried out by The Tennessean and The Indianapolis Star indicate at least five of Rinehart's patients died due to drugs he prescribed between March 2015 and January 2016. Another six patients suffered nonfatal overdoses between 2014 and 2016 according to the investigation.
Rinehart told the medical board he was ignorant of safe prescribing laws the Associated Press reported.
The charges against the former local doctor are part of a national crackdown which included 60 medical professionals from seven states in what is considered to be the single-largest prescription opioid law enforcement operation in U.S. history.
With a total of 32 medical professionals charged from the Volunteer State more than half of the 60 defendants in the national operation are from Tennessee. Nine people are facing charges from Middle Tennessee following the national operation.
Jeff Young a nurse practitioner from Jackson is accused of trading fentanyl patches for sex.
Dr. Timothy Abbott a South Nashville Podiatrist is charged with seven counts of prescribing a controlled substance without a legitimate medical purpose
Medical professionals in Kentucky Louisiana Ohio West Virginia Alabama and Pennsylvania were all charged in the massive takedown. Across all states the suspects included 31 doctors seven pharmacists eight nurse practitioners and seven other licensed medical professionals according to a Department of Justice news release.
The opioid epidemic is the deadliest drug crisis in American history and Appalachia has suffered the consequences more than perhaps any other region said U.S. Attorney General William Barr in a press release on the operation. But the Department of Justice is doing its part to help end this crisis.
With a total of 6052014 painkiller prescriptions across the state there were 1304 deaths caused by opiod overdoses in 2018 according to a report from the Tennessee Department of Health.
Last year 23 people died from drug overdoses in Maury County 18 which were opioid overdose deaths and 3 involved heroine.
In 2017 the county recorded 246 nonfatal overdose outpatient visits and 96 nonfatal overdose inpatient stays.
The department indicates nearly three fourths of drug overdose deaths in Tennessee in 2017 were associated with opioids. There were 1268 overdose deaths associated with all opioids and of those 644 were associated with prescription opioids for pain which include drugs such as hydrocodone oxycodone morphine and codeine. Those drugs were associated with more overdose deaths than any other group of drugs for the year.
In 2014 a total of 1263 died from drug-related overdoses in the state. In 2015 that number increased to 1451 and again in 2016 to 1631 with an estimated 432000 people in need of recovery resources. Drug overdoses are also the number one cause of death of people under age 55.
Tennessee families will soon receive state-funded assistance to battle addiction and keep children out of foster care.
On Monday the Tennessee Department of Mental Health and Substance Abuse announced a 5-year 3 million program designed to help families and children affected by opioids and other substance abuse by addressing addiction improving permanency and enhancing the safety of children in affected households.
When addiction hits a person it impacts their whole family in ways that will be felt for years to come said Commissioner Marie Williams in a press release. Weve seen time and time again that if a person can achieve recovery they can unlock the door to being the parent they always wanted to be.
Tennessee is among the hardest-hit states by the opioid epidemic a crisis now known to have been aided by pharmaceutical companies misrepresenting the addictive nature of opioids during the 1990s and encouraging prescriptions. The over-prescription played a major role in widespread misuse and rural areas were particularly hard-hit.
In 2017 the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services declared the U.S. Opioid Epidemic a public health emergency.
In Tennessee there were 2388 opioid overdose deaths in 2020 more than 4 million painkiller prescriptions in 2021 and 824 babies born with neonatal abstinence syndrome in 2020 according to the Tennessee Department Health.
Because the opioid crisis has primarily affected rural counties Tennessee and its partners will be focusing on nine counties in Middle Tennessee Bedford Coffee Franklin Giles Hickman Lawrence Lincoln Marshall and Maury counties.
Families will be provided intensive in-home crisis intervention and life skills education to help them fight addiction and create better home lives for children.
Because the services are coming to them travel expenses and other barriers preventing families from receiving care should no longer be an issue said Matthew Parriot spokesman for the Department of Mental Health.
The desired outcome is to avoid out of home placement at the end of the day everyone wants the same thing to keep the family together because thats whats best for the kids he said.
The department is also partnering with the Tennessee Department of Childrens Services Department of Human Services the Administrative Office of the Courts and Centerstone a nonprofit organization providing crisis-intervention services.
Grant funding for the program runs through September 2027.
Tennessees mental health department runs a similar program called Therapeutic Intervention Education and Skills TIES to assist children up to 18 years old at risk of being placed in foster care due to their caregivers substance abuse.
Dr. Darrel Rinehart had at least 5 patients die from overdoses in less than a year.
Rinehart has been indicted federally for overprescribing opioids.
State prosecutors were also preparing to charge him with reckless homicide.
Tennessee law enforcement were pursuing reckless homicide charges against an overprescribing doctor who had 5 patients die of overdoses in one year but recently passed the investigation to federal prosecutors as part of a massive opioid crackdown.
Dr. Darrel Rinehart 63 who practiced for decades in Columbia but moved to Indiana after his prescriptions were questioned was arrested two weeks ago on federal drug charges. He was one of 31 doctors indicted across six states in a sweeping effort to combat the opioid crisis in criminal court.
However if Rinehart had not been indicted in federal court he would likely have still been arrested.
Maury County District Attorney Brent Cooper confirmed this week that his office was nearly ready to present a grand jury with five charges of reckless homicide against Rinehart but Cooper gave their case to federal prosecutors because federal drug crimes would be easier to prove and carried harsher punishments. A reckless homicide prosecution in state court would not be an easy case to win Cooper said.
People in this area hold doctors in very high esteem Cooper said. I think convincing 12 citizens beyond a reasonable doubt that what Dr. Rinehart did amounts to reckless homicide would have some difficulties. But I dont think it would be impossible and we were certainly going to try if the federal authorities had not reached out to us first.
Rinehart who practiced in Columbia for two decades was the subject of a joint investigation by The Tennessean and The Indianapolis Star that published earlier this year. The investigation revealed at least five of Rineharts patients suffered fatal overdoses that were partially or wholly caused by drugs he prescribed between March 2015 and January 2016 and health officials were also suspicious of two more deaths of patients who were taking Rineharts prescriptions. Six more Rinehart patients had nonfatal overdoses between 2014 and 2016 including one patient who overdosed three times.
In several cases Rinehart gave his patients whopping prescriptions  despite red flags of abuse  only a few days before they died.
Cooper said that federal prosecutors contacted him after The TennesseanIndianapolis Star story published interested in taking command of his ongoing Rinehart investigation. The investigation was all but completed Cooper said but it was clear the case would be stronger in federal court.
After discussing it with them we realized the federal charges they could potentially charge Dr. Rinehart with carried a much longer sentence than reckless homicide on the state level Cooper said. We also had issues with one or two of our cases where we were close to running out the statue of limitation on some of the earliest overdose deaths.
Ultimately federal prosecutors indicted Rinehart on 19 counts of prescribing controlled substances without a legitimate medical purpose. Court records say those prescriptions went to four patients all of whom died while under Rineharts care.
Rinehart is not facing federal homicide charges. Cooper said his office is no longer planning to prosecute Rinehart in state court.
Rinehart pleaded not guilty to all charges during his first court appearance on April 22. He declined to comment when questioned by a reporter.
