Slatery alleges among other things that Walgreens did not properly train pharmacists to recognize red flags for patient opioid abuse regularly sold huge quantities of high-risk drug combinations to patients did not properly take into account suspicious prescribers and prescribed suspiciously high doses of the drug to patients.
Walgreens' spokesman Fraser Engerman defended the company's actions.
Walgreens never manufactured or marketed opioids nor did we distribute them to the pain clinics and 'pill mills' that fueled this crisis Engerman wrote in an email. We will continue to defend against the unjustified attacks on the professionalism of our pharmacists dedicated healthcare professionals who live in the communities they serve.
Walgreens recently settled a similar claim filed by the state of Florida. According to the terms of that 683 million settlement the company paid 620 million to the state to be paid out over 18 years and a one-time payment of 63 million for attorneys' fees.
The deal did not include an admission of wrongdoing by Walgreens.
Tennessee won a 15.2 million share of a multi-state settlement with consulting firm McKinsey  Company last year over its promotion of opioid drugs. It similarly won a share of a 4.5 billion settlement with Purdue Pharma and a settlement with Endo Pharmaceuticals. Other lawsuits include those against AmericsoureBergen Drug Corp. and Food City Supermarkets LLC and K-VA-T Food Stores Inc.
