Rookie Officer Jessica Johann was riding shotgun with her partner on Jan. 26 when they first spotted the white pickup truck weaving between traffic and speeding down the shoulder of Interstate 40.
They flipped on their lights and siren then Johann prepared herself for a chase. If the motorist was willing to drive like this she thought then he was probably willing to run.
The way he was driving the way he was weaving it seemed like intoxication or aggression Johann said. I knew it was something bad and I didnt think he was going to pull over for us.
A moment later the driver had surprised her. He had swerved to the side of the highway and slammed the brakes as if he was anxious to get pulled over. A man then jumped out of the truck shouting that his friend was having an overdose. They were driving to rehab the man said and his friend wanted one last high before he gave it up for good.
Johann rushed to the car to look inside. In the passenger seat a young man sat stiff with his eyelids drooped his chin tilted up and his mouth gaping open. His eyes were gray and his lips were turning blue. Every breath he took was a desperate gasp.
Johann signaled back to her patrol car telling her partner to call an ambulance. A moment later her partner was at her side with a Narcan kit. Johann thought back to her training tore open the package and sprayed a dose in one nostril.
Im sure it was only a minute but it felt like the longest minute ever Johann said describing the incident in detail for the first time. It didnt seem like the Narcan was helping  It was at that instant I thought maybe he would die before the paramedics could even get there.
Johann gave the man another dose.
A minute passed.
Then another.
His mouth closed and his eyes fluttered open. He lifted his head.
Hey Johann shouted caught by surprise. Dont ever do that again
The man looked at her confused as color seeped back into his face.
OK.
