Nick Salazar didnt think he was an addict because he didnt live on urban city streets.
He lived instead in his parents house in suburban New Jersey.
I thought I have a job so Im OK. Im not homeless so Im OK  recalled Salazar.
He didnt think he was an addict because he took prescription pills not heroin.
Then one day he took heroin because he was short on the cash to buy pills.
It was only going to be a one-time fix and then he would go back to pills  because that was better somehow.
But it wasnt for one day. Heroin was cheaper.
I thought Im not shooting it. I snort it or smoke it. Again that told me I wasnt a drug addict he said.
I had this idea I grew up in this upper-middle class suburb in New Jersey. I grew up with this idea of what an addict was and where an addict was and that did not fit with what I saw in my town.
Addicts are in almost every town in Tennessee and the U.S. At least 1263 people died from overdose in the state in 2014.
Yet it wasnt until Salazar now 26 moved from Summit N.J. to Nashville to get help at Cumberland Heights that he realized he wasnt alone and that an addict can be anyone anywhere.
Overdose deaths reach 'epidemic proportions'
What Ive seen more and more talking to my friends is addicts are everywhere he said. Opiates and heroin are everywhere.
Salazar has been clean for three-and-a-half years. He made a group of friends most of whom are recovering from substance abuse and decided to stay in Nashville.
He married this summer and expects to graduate from Belmont University in three semesters. Hes passionate about substance abuse and helps others who are in rehab.
There are people all across the state with experiences such as his.
He started with Vicodin and Percocet from people who had wisdom teeth removed or were being treated for sports injuries.
Article continues below photo.
Then he moved to Oxycontin. At his peak of tolerance he spent about 200 a day to get his fix.
Heroin  used in the late 19th century as a cough suppressant and ironically as a treatment to opioid addiction  was next.
I had this idea this stigma in my mind about using it it was a line I didnt want to cross Salazar said. I had in my mind that pills were somehow safe and better because they were from a doctor not my doctor but a doctor.
Heroin was a step too far until it wasn't. He spent about 100 a day at his peak of heroin use.
The addiction took over his life. He woke up thinking about his next fix.
It became more important to me than anything else Salazar said.
He tried to get clean. Sometimes he took less. He never had a close call with an overdose but he felt resigned to his life and at times almost wanted to take too much.
Now he wants to write and direct TV shows and movies. He thinks about recovery every day but not the drugs and addiction.
In the early days of treatment using was an obsession.
Recovery is something I work on every day he said. I really wanted to get clean more than I wanted to get high so I did things to treat that disease.
