When he spotted his 11-month-old daughter she had white residue on her lips.
She was having difficulty breathing  her body battling a mixture of cocaine and fentanyl  close to becoming one of the youngest overdose victims in Nashville.
The child was treated at Centennial Medical Center's Children's Hospital. She is expected to make a full recovery.
Dozens arent so lucky.
Fatal drug overdoses in Nashville declined during the first quarter of 2023 but still netted 93 confirmed deaths with 49 pending. During the first three months of 2022 officials counted 193 fatal overdose deaths.
Related emergency room visits dropped slightly during the same period  from 525 2022 to 499 2023. Also three out of four overdose-related toxicology reports during the first quarter of 2023 contained fentanyl.
1999-2021 Child deaths nationally from fentanyl increased
Nationally the picture is more grim. One recent study published in JAMA Pediatrics found that child deaths from fentanyl increased sharply between 1999 and 2021. Fifteen years ago 5 of opioid deaths in children were caused by fentanyl according to the study. By 2021 fentanyl was responsible for 94 of such deaths that study found.
The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention also reported earlier this year that overdose deaths from fentanyl jumped 279 from 2016 to 2021.
How Nashville is getting serious about overdose deaths
The medical emergency in Nashville came to the attention of local authorities when the father informed them that his daughter pulled a piece of paper from a bathroom garbage can and placed it in her mouth. He initially denied responsibility for the fentanyl then later admitted to purchasing the illegal narcotics and discarding them in the home.
Officers located a straw on a living room table and a lottery ticket with a white powdery substance still on it.
Officials notified the Department of Childrens Services which provided services to the childs mother she was not present at the time her daughter ingested the fentanyl. This investigation is ongoing.
This case and others explain why Nashville is getting serious about curbing overdose deaths especially along Lower Broadway where 30 bars including Whiskey Row and Frank Sinatra Lounge now store Naloxone also known as Narcan an opioid reversal medication on-site.
Also Gibson Gives a charitable organization under Gibson Guitars launched TEMPO Training and Empowering Musicians to Prevent Overdoses. The program places the kits which cost around 350 in Nashville music venues.
